================================================================
PRACTICAL 9(c) - Demonstrate Exception Handling in UiPath
================================================================

DIFFICULTY: Medium

WHAT YOU WILL DO:
You will demonstrate TWO types of exception handling:
  (i)  Array Index Out of Bounds exception
  (ii) Division by Zero exception

--- STEP-BY-STEP INSTRUCTIONS ---

PART 1 - TRY CATCH ACTIVITY

Step 1: Open UiPath Studio → New Project.
  - Name it: Practical_9c_ExceptionHandling

Step 2: From the Activities panel, search "Try Catch" and drag it 
        into the Main sequence.
  - A Try Catch activity has 3 sections:
    TRY     → put the code that might throw an error
    CATCHES → define what happens when a specific error occurs
    FINALLY → runs regardless (cleanup code)

--- (i) ARRAY INDEX OUT OF BOUNDS ---

Step 3: Inside the TRY section, drag an "Assign" activity.
  - Create a variable: myArray (type: Array of [Int32])
  - In the Assign:
    - Left: myArray
    - Right: New Integer() {10, 20, 30}
    (This creates an array with 3 elements at index 0, 1, 2)

Step 4: Inside TRY, below Assign, drag another "Assign" activity.
  - Left: result (type: Int32)
  - Right: myArray(5)
  ← This tries to access index 5 which doesn't exist → will throw an error

Step 5: Click the "+" button in the CATCHES section.
  - Exception Type: System.IndexOutOfRangeException
    (Start typing "IndexOutOfRange" and select from dropdown)
  - Inside the catch body, drag a "Message Box".
    - Text: "Error caught! Array index is out of range. 
             The array only has 3 elements (index 0-2)."

Step 6: In the FINALLY section (optional):
  - Drag a "Message Box" → Text: "Finally block executed — cleanup done."

Step 7: Run (F5).
  - The error will be caught gracefully.
  - Message Box will show the friendly error message.
  - Then the Finally block message will appear.
  - The workflow will NOT crash!

--- (ii) DIVISION BY ZERO EXCEPTION ---

Step 8: Add a new "Try Catch" activity below the first one.

Step 9: In the TRY section:
  - Drag an "Assign" activity.
  - Left: divResult (type: Int32)
  - Right: 10 / 0
  ← Dividing by zero throws DivideByZeroException

Step 10: In the CATCHES section → click "+" to add exception type.
  - Exception Type: System.DivideByZeroException
  - Inside catch body, drag "Message Box":
    - Text: "Error caught! Cannot divide by zero. 
             Please check your input values."

Step 11: Run (F5).
  - The division by zero error is caught.
  - Friendly message appears instead of a crash.

SUMMARY TABLE:
  Exception Type                  | What causes it
  --------------------------------|-------------------------------
  System.IndexOutOfRangeException | Accessing array index that doesn't exist
  System.DivideByZeroException    | Dividing a number by zero
  System.NullReferenceException   | Using a variable that has no value (null)
  System.Exception                | Catch-all for any error

BEST PRACTICES:
  - Always use specific exception types (not just System.Exception) 
    when you know what error to expect.
  - Use the FINALLY block for cleanup (closing files, logging, etc.)
  - Log errors using "Log Message" activity for production workflows.

